pagemap: {"cse_thumbnail": [{"width": "188", "height": "268", "src": "https://encrypted-tbn1.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcT5hTjfl8nnNCa9y-T7FWTXP6ZvPUlGOLBHE_CxRlqtbZ8rwJHwDZQOefjw"}], "metatags": [{"viewport": "width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0", "gs_meta_revision": "1.1", "citation_journal_title": "Linguistica", "citation_journal_abbrev": "1", "citation_issn": "2350-420X", "citation_author": "Eva Sicherl", "citation_author_institution": "University of Ljubljana", "citation_title": "The English-Slovene language contact: borrowing of personal names", "citation_date": "2015/12/31", "citation_volume": "55", "citation_issue": "1", "citation_firstpage": "273", "citation_lastpage": "289", "citation_doi": "10.4312/linguistica.55.1.273-289", "citation_abstract_html_url": "https://revije.ff.uni-lj.si/linguistica/article/view/6316", "citation_keywords": "pragmatic borrowing", "citation_pdf_url": "https://revije.ff.uni-lj.si/linguistica/article/download/6316/6044", "dc.creator.personalname": "Eva Sicherl", "dc.date.created": "2015-12-31", "dc.date.datesubmitted": "2016-03-16", "dc.date.issued": "2015-12-31", "dc.date.modified": "2016-03-16", "dc.description": "The article aims to shed some light on the growing tendency of Slovene native speakers towards borrowing English personal names when naming new-born children. Some historical overview of the borrowing of English personal names into Slovene is given, starting with lists compiled from 1931 onwards, established from the data supplied by the Statistical Office of the Republic of Slovenia (SURS). The phenomenon of borrowing personal names is discussed from the point of view of pragmatic borrowing as advocated by G. Andersen (2014), taking into account the traditional distinction between necessary loans on the one hand and luxury loans on the other. The article illustrates how in the case of personal names, \u2018exoticisms\u2019 (e.g. Alex, Liam, Kevin, Kim, Ian, Vanessa, Adrian, Ella, Emma, Patrick, Nick, Alan, Lucas, listed among the most popular 200 first names in the 2001\u20132013 period) compete with name forms that have been adapted and nativised long ago (e.g. Patrik), or are currently being introduced for the firs", "dc.format": "application/pdf", "dc.identifier": "6316", "dc.identifier.pagenumber": "273-289", "dc.identifier.doi": "10.4312/linguistica.55.1.273-289", "dc.identifier.uri": "https://revije.ff.uni-lj.si/linguistica/article/view/6316", "dc.language": "en", "dc.rights": "Copyright (c) 2016 Eva Sicherl", "dc.source": "Linguistica", "dc.source.issn": "2350-420X", "dc.source.issue": "1", "dc.source.volume": "55", "dc.source.uri": "https://revije.ff.uni-lj.si/linguistica", "dc.subject": "pragmatic borrowing", "dc.title": "The English-Slovene language contact: borrowing of personal names", "dc.title.alternative": "Angle\u0161ko-slovenski jezikovni stik: izposojanje osebnih imen", "dc.type": "Text.Serial.Journal", "dc.type.articletype": "Articles"}], "cse_image": [{"src": "https://revije.ff.uni-lj.si/public/journals/3/cover_issue_528_en_US.jpg"}]}
